    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-01-02T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-01-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="536"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d536">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName> Papers: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_CC2" type="from"
                            >Churchill</persName> to President <persName corresp="#p_RFD1" type="to"
                            >Roosevelt</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d536fn1">Presumably sent via military channels.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-02">2 January
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>530. Prime Minister to President <persName corresp="#p_RFD1"
                    >Roosevelt</persName>. Personal.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_HC1">Hull</persName> tells <persName corresp="#p_EA1"
                        >Eden</persName> that you have no recollection of any remarks by <gloss
                        target="#t_UJ1">UJ</gloss> about unconditional surrender.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d536fn2">See <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_855">p.
                            855</ref>.</note> I certainly heard, with great interest, <pb
                        facs="0967" n="863" xml:id="pg_863"/> him saying something to the effect
                    that he thought it might be well to consider telling the Germans at some stage
                    what unconditional surrender would involve, or perhaps what it would not
                    involve. After that we began talking about the 50,000 and your compromise and my
                    high falutin, and I finished up by no means certain that the Germans would be
                    reassured if they were told what he had in mind.<note n="3" xml:id="d536fn3">
                        <persName corresp="#p_CC2">Churchill</persName>’s reference is to the
                        discussion at the dinner meeting on November 29, 1943; see <hi rend="italic"
                            >ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_554">p. 554</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Find also <persName corresp="#p_BAJD1">Anthony</persName> telegraphed to the
                    Foreign Office on November 30 as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“Last night (November 29th) Marshal <persName corresp="#p_SIV1"
                                >Stalin</persName> spoke to the President about unconditional
                            surrender. Marshal <persName corresp="#p_SIV1">Stalin</persName> said he
                            considered this bad tactics vis-à-vis Germany and his suggestion was
                            that we should together work out terms and let them be made known
                            generally to the people of Germany”.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Perhaps this may give you a cue to what <persName corresp="#p_BAJD1"
                        >Anthony</persName> and I had in our memories and you may feel inclined to
                    join with us in asking <gloss target="#t_UJ1">UJ</gloss> whether he would care
                    to develop his theme to us. If however, you prefer we can of course leave things
                    where they are for the time being.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
